The emancipation tied former serfs to communal farming (*mir*) with onerous obligations, perpetuating poverty and resistance to change, while conservative nobles retained power and wealth, delaying meaningful reform. The system’s flaws—like redemption payments and collective responsibility—stifled individual initiative and economic mobility. While later reforms (e.g., Stolypin’s) addressed some issues, the initial terms reinforced rural stagnation and conservative dominance.
